digraph G {
    rankdir=LR;
    node [shape=record];

    Potentiometer -> Buffer -> LowPassFilter -> GainStage -> AntiAliasingFilter -> DAQ;

    Potentiometer [label="Potentiometer"];
    Buffer [label="Buffer"];
    LowPassFilter [label="Low-Pass Filter\n(50/60 Hz notch)"];
    GainStage [label="Gain Stage"];
    AntiAliasingFilter [label="Anti-Aliasing Filter"];
    DAQ [label="Data Acquisition\n(DAQ) System"];
}
```

```Explanations
Potentiometer: This is a 10 kOhms linear potentiometer connected to the pendulum. As the pendulum swings, the resistance changes proportionally to the angle of displacement. The potentiometer provides a variable voltage output that is directly related to the angle of the pendulum.

Buffer: A buffer stage is used to prevent the potentiometer from being loaded by subsequent stages. It provides a high input impedance to avoid altering the potentiometer's output characteristics and a low output impedance to drive the next stages effectively.

Low-Pass Filter: A low-pass filter with notch characteristics at 50/60 Hz is implemented to attenuate any power line noise that may be picked up by the potentiometer. This helps in ensuring that the signal entering the gain stage is as clean as possible, reducing the likelihood of aliasing and improving the accuracy of the measurement.

Gain Stage: To ensure that the voltage levels are within the acceptable range of the DAQ system, a gain stage is used to amplify the signal from the potentiometer. The gain is set so that the potentiometer's full swing corresponds to the full input voltage range of the DAQ system (Â±7 V).

Anti-Aliasing Filter: Before the signal is digitized by the DAQ, an anti-aliasing filter is used to remove any high-frequency components that could cause aliasing. This analog filter passes the desired signal and attenuates frequencies above the Nyquist rate of the DAQ system, ensuring an accurate digital representation of the analog signal.

DAQ (Data Acquisition System): This is the final stage where the conditioned analog signal is converted into a digital format for further processing or analysis. The DAQ system captures the voltage levels, which can then be converted to angular measurements using appropriate scaling factors.
```

